          "body": "Verse 7 introduces the pur — the lot — and the narrator pauses to explain the word ('Pur, that is the lot') before recording its result. Haman casts it 'from day to day and from month to month' — a month-long process of divination to determine the most favorable day for his plan. What he receives is the twelfth month, Adar, roughly eleven months distant. From Haman's perspective, this may have seemed inauspicious; from the narrative's perspective, it is the hinge on which the entire story turns. The pur that was meant to identify the perfect moment for genocide becomes, in Proverbs 16:33's terms, 'cast into the lap, but its every decision is from the Lord.' God is never named in Esther 3, but the lot's result is the most theologically freighted moment in the chapter. The name of the Jewish feast — Purim — will derive precisely from this lot (9:24-26), transforming the instrument of Haman's plan into the memorial of his defeat. What the enemy cast for destruction, God was already converting into the occasion for deliverance."
