    "intro": "Interpretation moves from what Esther 3 says to what it means — tracing the author's intent within the book's theological argument, its place in the Hebrew canon, and its purchase on the reader's understanding of God, evil, and covenant fidelity. Esther 3 is the chapter that makes the book necessary: without the decree, there is no crisis; without the crisis, no deliverance; without the deliverance, no Purim and no demonstration that God's covenant commitment to His people is not contingent on their political circumstances.",
