        "range": "3:1",
        "excerpt": "King Ahasuerus promoted Haman, the son of Hammedatha the Agagite, and advanced him and established his authority over all the princes who were with him.",
        "body": "The chapter's first verse is its most theologically dense. The narrator does not simply introduce an antagonist; he names his lineage with canonical precision. 'The Agagite' is not ethnic color — it is a theological signal to every reader who knows the history of 1 Samuel 15. Agag was the Amalekite king whose survival (in defiance of God's command through Samuel) marked the decisive failure of Saul's kingship and led to his rejection (1 Samuel 15:10-11). The Amalekites are Israel's oldest enemy — the people who attacked the weak and weary at the Exodus (Deuteronomy 25:17-19) and whom God declared perpetual war against (Exodus 17:14-16).\n\nMordecai is identified as a Benjaminite, a descendant of Kish (2:5) — the same tribal and familial line as Saul ben Kish. The narrator has constructed a deliberate genealogical irony: the descendants of the two men whose confrontation in 1 Samuel 15 should have ended the Amalekite threat are now facing each other in the Persian court. Saul's disobedience had consequences that would not resolve for centuries. The reader who catches this connection understands that Esther 3 is not merely a palace intrigue — it is the resumption of a cosmic conflict between the seed of the Serpent and the covenant people.\n\nThis canonical depth is why the narrator names Haman as 'the enemy of the Jews' (3:10) — a title that precedes any demonstration of his enmity in that verse. The narrator's label is a verdict reached through the logic of genealogy and covenant history, not merely through the events of this chapter. Haman is the enemy of the Jews because of who he is and whose son he is, before he does anything.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Agagi* (Agagite) — the gentillic form of Agag, the Amalekite king. *Gadal* (honored/promoted, 3:1) — the same verb used of Abraham's blessing in Genesis 12:2 and Joseph's elevation in Genesis 41:40. The irony is that the verb of covenant elevation is applied to covenant's enemy."
