        "excerpt": "Pur, that is the lot, was cast before Haman from day to day and from month to month, until the twelfth month, that is the month Adar.",
        "body": "Verse 7 is structurally isolated in the chapter — it stands between Haman's rage (3:5-6) and his petition to the king (3:8-9), a single verse of calendar-consultation before the political execution of his plan. Yet it is arguably the most theologically rich verse in the chapter, and perhaps in the book.\n\nHaman uses the pur — a Persian practice of casting lots to determine propitious timing — to select the date for his genocide. He casts it 'from day to day and from month to month,' working through the entire calendar. What he receives is the twelfth month, Adar: nearly a full year away. The narrator does not comment. He does not say 'but God.' He does not invoke providence. He simply records the result and moves on.\n\nBut the result is the story's hinge. An eleven-month delay is what makes everything in chapters 4–8 possible. Without it, Haman's decree would have been executed before Esther could act, before Mordecai could persuade her, before the king's sleepless night (6:1) could surface the unrewarded record of Mordecai's loyalty. The lot — the instrument of pagan divination, intended to give Haman a perfect killing day — produces the very window of time in which the covenant community can be saved.\n\nProverbs 16:33 is the canonical lens: 'The lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from the Lord.' The book of Esther embeds this theology in narrative without naming it. God is never mentioned. But the lot's result is the clearest finger of divine governance in the chapter. The feast of Purim — whose name derives from this very word, pur — is therefore not named for Haman's plan but for its failure. God took the instrument of Haman's timing and made it the name of Israel's celebration of survival.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pur* — a Persian loanword for the lot, explained by the narrator with the Hebrew equivalent *goral*. The narrator's gloss ('that is the lot') is itself evidence of authorial intention to ensure no reader misses the theological import of the word. *Naphal* (was cast, 3:7) — the same verb used for the lot's fall in Joshua 18-19 (the allotment of the land). The lots fall; God governs their landing."
